<paragraph blockId="5.[151,684,753,903]" pageId="5" pageNumber="12">
<taxonomicName authorityName="T. G. Hartley" authorityYear="2003" box="[177,413,754,780]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rutaceae" genus="Neoschmidia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="5" pageNumber="12" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="calycina">
<emphasis box="[177,413,754,780]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="12">Neoschmidia calycina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName box="[569,683,753,780]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rutaceae" genus="Neoschmidia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="5" pageNumber="12" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pallida">
<emphasis box="[569,683,753,780]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="12">N. pallida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
mainly in its sepals, which are connate in their proximal 1/3-1/2 and have a free portion 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.15" metricValueMax="1.5" metricValueMin="0.8" pageId="5" pageNumber="12" unit="mm" value="1.15" valueMax="1.5" valueMin="0.8">0.8- 1.5 mm</quantity>
long. Also, it lacks the sericeous indumentum seen in 
<taxonomicName box="[332,439,876,903]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rutaceae" genus="Neoschmidia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="5" pageNumber="12" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pallida">
<emphasis box="[332,439,876,903]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="12">N. pallida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
